1. Introduction

This document explores the atmospheric concentration of CO2. First, installing the packages called “prophet” using “install.packages()” function in R. This package is a default version, not the latest one. This is done inside the console and hence, it will not appear in the “.RMD” file.

2. Dataset of Atmospheric Concentration of CO2

co2 is a time series embedded in R with 468 observations consist of monthly data from 1959 to 1997. The goal is to figure out the atmospheric concentration of CO2 over the years and try to forecast the future trend based on existing CO2 data.

library("prophet")
## Loading required package: Rcpp
## Loading required package: rlang
ds= zoo::as.yearmon(time(co2))
y= co2
co2_dataframe = data.frame(ds, y)
plot(co2_dataframe)

From the above code, ds is the time of the observations in year while y is the atmospheric concentration of CO2 in parts per million (ppm). Due to the identical movements of ups and downs from the graph above, it is worth noticing that the mean and variance of this model is constant.

linear_model <- lm(y ~ ds)
summary(linear_model)

Based on initial plot of CO2 data againsts time, there is a linear relationship trend. By looking at the summary of this model, the multiple r-squared is 96.95% which is quite high, and can implies that the model fits linear regression quite accurately. However to see in depth if this data is suitable or not to fit linearity, linear regression is used with linear assumptions.

3. Linear Assumptions

plot(linear_model)

From the above code, 4 different plots are obtained:

  1. Standard residuals against fitted value

This plot has a U-shaped pattern and does not scatter evenly. Here, one of the suggestions could be is to make a log-transformation so that it appears more disperse, satisfying the linear assumption. With regard of that, this model may not have a constant variance.

  1. Q-Q Residuals

This plot shows that all of the middle points follow Normal distribution plot. However, the plot starts to get further than the Normal distribution plot on the both ends. Hence, suggesting this model may not follow Normal distribution.

  1. Scale-Location

This plot will show us about the homoscedasticity just like plot “1”. Unlike “1.”, all the points are scattered throughout the plot. However when look closely, the points does not scatter evenly but rather a little bit dense on the middle of this graph. Hence, the assumption of constant variance does not hold necessarily.

  1. Residuals vs Leverage

This plot has a dense segments at ds= 0.002, which suggests this model may have a high leverage on this coordinate. However, by referring to the original plot, there is no visible outliers.

Overall, the model does not follow linear assumptions, where it contradicts with the result from the summary and may not have a constant variance as what has been observed initially. From the original plot, we can see a linear relationship trend however, after further research on whether the model follows the linearity assumptions, it seems like the model is not suitable to make it linear. Nevertheless, we will do a forecast for the concentration of CO2 for the next 20 years where it is expected to have increasing trend (initially).

4. Forecasting

To do the forecasting, a model is created by utilising “prophet()” function in R which has been installed prior to this step. This is named as “model” where a forecast is made along with the historical data for the next 20 years for the period of 240 months. Here, 240 months indicates that the forecast shown is for the next 20 years where the data will be “collected” monthly. This step is shown in the code below.

model = prophet(co2_dataframe, weekly.seasonality = TRUE, daily.seasonality = TRUE)
future = make_future_dataframe(model, periods= 240, freq="month")
predict = predict(model, future)
x <- plot(model, predict)

From the above code, “future” is a data frame containing dates interested for the future prediction. Since this forecast is for the next 20 years with monthly frequency, hence the period used will be “240”.

Moreover, the “predict()” function takes the “model” and a data frame of future dates where it is named as “future”, both as input (these two variables have been mentioned above). With these two inputs, it will return a data frame named as a “predict” variable containing the predictions made by the Prophet model for the chosen future dates.

After doing the forecasting, it looks like a linear trend. However there’s dispersion at the forecast suggesting the range of graph would be not necessarily linear. This also can be seen from the value of “yhat”, “yhat_lower” and “yhat_upper”.

tail(predict[c("yhat_lower", "yhat_upper", "yhat")])
##     yhat_lower yhat_upper     yhat
## 703   359.9177   425.4659 392.8002
## 704   357.6222   423.8872 390.7931
## 705   355.6212   422.4159 389.1462
## 706   355.6494   422.4324 389.1724
## 707   356.7939   423.5773 390.3854
## 708   357.8379   425.3287 391.6443

As the time of forecasting increases, the predicted value of y with its confidence interval gets bigger. This may happen as the longer the forecasting is, the higher the uncertainty it might be when trying to predict the future trend. Hence this will show a significant difference between upper and lower bound. This might also help to argue with the linearity assumptions discussed above. Due to the uncertainty of the future trend, this model might not suitable to be fitted into linear regression line.

Now, the time series is decomposed for further discussion.

prophet::prophet_plot_components(model, predict)

The above code implies that the time series is decomposed into multiple plots. The “prophet::” is used to specify that the “prophet” package is utilised to plot this components. Although the package was loaded using “library()” function earlier, but it does not work when using the “prophet_plot_components()” function. Nevertheless, the plots consist of trend, weekly seasonality, yearly seasonality and daily seasonality.

  1. Trend

It shows an increasing time series. This is not a shocking finding as primarily concentration of CO2 is known to increase gradually due to human activities. For example, activities such as deforestation and burning of fossil fuels is now actively done by human to provide economic growth and demand for big corporations.

  1. Yearly Seasonality

It can be seen that during the summer, the atmospheric concentration of CO2 is higher. This mainly happens due to hot weather where people frequently use air-conditioner to cool themselves and to avoid being uncomfortable.

  1. Daily Seasonality

Although it seems weird that the atmospheric concentration of CO2 is higher during the night time, but it is worth stressing that during the hour, there is still a lot of other human activities happen. For example, there will be a lot of commuting for deliveries worker, either through land, sea or air.

4. Conclusions

It is important to understand the pattern or trend of things around us. In this case, it is atmospheric concentration of CO2, whether the trend is in the past, present or future. With this understanding, it will help give a better insight to us on how to mitigate or avoid catastrophic event, climate change effects and many more.
